import Moat from './Moat.astro';
---

<ActBreak
  roman="Act VI"
  title="A Guardrail Below"
  accent="the Prompt"
  tease="The payoff: a jailbreak defense that reads intent, not wording — so it can't be talked out of the way."
  id="act-6"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="harden">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">16</span> The threat</div>
    <h2>Every attacker comes through the same door</h2>

    <p>
      Step back and ask what all this research is <em>for</em>. Here's the answer, and it starts
      with a simple observation: whoever attacks a deployed AI — trying to extract harmful
      instructions with roleplay tricks, "ignore your instructions" gambits, jailbreak
      wrappers — can only reach it through <strong>the prompt</strong>. The text box. That's the
      one door. Everything you've read so far built the tools to guard it from a place the
      attacker can't reach: <em>inside</em> the model, below the prompt.
    </p>

    <p>
      First, the obvious approach — and its failure. Use the pen to push the model toward refusal
      <em>all the time</em>, for everyone. It does cut attacks. It also refuses
      <strong>100% of innocent requests</strong> on one model — a security guard who solves theft
      by locking out all the customers. On another model it did something worse than nothing:
      constant pushing made attacks <em>more</em> successful, 58% → 92%. Both failures were sealed
      bets, both are on the record.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_harden"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 14"
      alt="Attack success and innocent-request refusal per defense strategy, plus writes per generation"
      caption="The blunt approach on trial. Timed pushing matches naive constant pushing on normal traffic at a fifth of the writes (11.8 vs 50 per generation) — but neither survives a determined attacker. A registered fail that pointed to the real design."
      gates={["gate_L23_harden"]}
    />

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">17</span> The idea that works</div>
    <h2>Recognize first. Then — and only then — defend.</h2>

    <p>
      The fix is the project's namesake idea — <em>recognition</em> — applied at the door.
      A good bouncer doesn't frisk every guest; he reads intent. It turns out jailbreak prompts
      carry a <strong>machine-readable signature of intent</strong> deep inside the model's
      activations, at a specific layer — and on the right models, that signature is unmistakable.
      On one test model, innocent requests all score in one range, attacks all in another, with
      <strong>clear daylight between them</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      So the defense fires <em>only</em> on recognition. The result on that model: attack success
      halved — the same cut the customer-locking approach achieved — at
      <strong>zero</strong> cost to innocent traffic. And because the signature is read from the
      model's internals rather than the prompt's wording, dressing the attack up in roleplay or
      "ignore previous instructions" costume changes nothing. The costume is words. The signature
      isn't.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_moat"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 15"
      alt="Attack success and innocent-refusal across four models and three defense strategies"
      caption="Four models, three strategies. Left: attack success under no defense, constant pushing, and recognition-gated defense. Right: the price paid in refused innocent requests. Where the signature separates cleanly, recognition gating matches the blunt approach's protection at a fraction of its cost."
      gates={["gate_L26_moat_proof", "gate_L26_moat_llama", "gate_L26_moat_qwen", "gate_L26_moat_smol"]}
    />

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">18</span> Knowing the limits</div>
    <h2>A pre-flight test tells you where it works</h2>

    <p>
      Now the part that makes this <em>shippable</em> rather than just interesting: the defense is
      not universal, and you can know in advance. Across four model families it protected two —
      and on the other two, the innocent and attack signatures overlap, so the recognition gate
      has nothing clean to read. The pre-deployment check is one offline measurement:
      <strong>do the two ranges separate?</strong> That test called the outcome correctly on
      <strong>all four</strong> models. Two passes, two fails — four correct predictions, made
      before deploying anything.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_cleangap"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 17"
      alt="Innocent and attack signature ranges per model, showing separation or overlap"
      caption="The pre-flight test. Grey: where innocent requests score. Coloured: where attacks score, per model. Separation predicts protection: 4 predictions, 4 correct."
      gates={["gate_L26_moat_*", "gate_char_*"]}
    />

    <div class="callout rose">
      <div class="callout-title">Scope, honestly</div>
      <p>
        These defense numbers are early-stage: a dozen attacks and ten innocent prompts per model,
        one seed, deterministic decoding. What's established is the <em>mechanism</em> and the
        pre-flight test's 4-for-4 record — not a benchmark-scale protection claim. The transcripts
        below are real, unedited captures.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

